    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Helping the Mentally Ill</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Jean Arnold lauds Sept 6 article examining innovative treatment program for people with serious mental illness developed in Ithaca, NY, in effort to prevent killer rampages</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>You deserve praise for examining the innovative treatment programs for people with serious mental illness developed in Ithaca, N.Y. (''Trying to Prevent the Next Killer Rampage,'' front page, Sept. 6). Everyone wins when experts head off a potential crisis. An even better approach, however, would be more high-quality community programs so that the police would not need to intervene.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>You deserve praise for examining the innovative treatment programs for people with serious mental illness developed in Ithaca, N.Y. (''Trying to Prevent the Next Killer Rampage,'' front page, Sept. 6). Everyone wins when experts head off a potential crisis. An even better approach, however, would be more high-quality community programs so that the police would not need to intervene.</p>
        <p>In the interest of accuracy and relevance, references to Kendra's Law, which makes it easier to commit mentally ill people who resist treatment, should mention that the man who pushed Kendra Webdale in front of a subway train had repeatedly begged for treatment and a safe place to live, but was turned away  by an unresponsive mental health system.</p>
        <p>JEAN ARNOLD  Chairwoman  National Stigma Clearinghouse  New York, Sept. 6, 2000</p>
      </block>
